!TITLE
WEEK FOUR
!WORDS
Week Four: Here we are at the end of another week full of 
indescribable preciousness and copious tears. Arlo moved from “I like 
you” to “I love you, baby” which fills me. Maeve started smiling 
which makes everyone giddy. 

Unfiltered: week four hit hard on the parents. We’re tired, not from 
the newborn stage—this round has felt easy in comparison to our first 
rodeo! But we’re tired from witnessing and helping our nearly-three 
year old through what has been the hardest moments of his little 
life. It’s emotionally, mentally and physically draining and 
eventually those tugs and pulls work their way into the marriage 
because everyone needs to discharge big feels. I am thankful for a 
partner who carries with him emotional awareness and stands together 
with us as we wait until the big wave is done with its force. 

After the big moments, we go outside wrapped in a blanket to listen 
to the birds or sing together on repeat: “I’ve got peace like a river 
in my soul!”

I’ve tried to write this post 100 times. I’ve made 100 different warm 
baths to wash the milk leaking from my body away, but I’ve had to 
stop, called away by a cry or crash. 

I texted my midwife in a moment of pure pandemonium to say, “This is 
a special form a chaos.”

“Yes, isn’t it wonderful!” She said back. 

And she’s right: this is the exact chaos I prayed for and I’m glad 
it’s mine! 

Now I’ll try to make my bath again, and whether it actually gets to 
happen or not doesn’t matter much, because I can always try again.


Sheena Jeffers  1/26/24
