!TITLE
SHAMELESS - A REVIEW
!WORDS
Sex-ed for those who love God but reject traditional church teachings 
on sex
Reviewed i11/15/20 

In her third and most recent book Shameless: A Sexual Reformation, 
unorthodox Lutheran Minister Nadia Bolz-Weber examines many of the 
more troubling and controversial messages of traditional Christian 
churches on the subject of sex and sexuality. As part of a call for 
churches and their parishioners to undergo an examination and an 
exploration of what their churches have taught on about sexual 
matters, she makes the case that the time has come (or more 
accurately, that it is long overdue) to reconsider and for the most 
part reject many church teachings on controversial subjects such as 
pre-marital abstinence, homosexuality, birth control, abortion, 
transgenderism, and pornography, among others. Her message is that 
rather than aspire to attain some impossible as well as impractical 
standard, and hate ourselves for our inability to attain that 
standard, we should instead accept and embrace our true selves, 
whether or not we measure up to the sexual standards set by 
traditional religion, so long as we aspire to follow the central New 
Testament commandment to "love thy neighbor as thyself."

The author is not your traditional old-style preacher. Heavily 
tattooed and purple-haired, the former stand-up comedian is a 
recovering alcoholic with over 20 years sobriety, a divorced mother 
of two college-aged children, whose language is frequently peppered 
with f-bombs and other swear-jar contributing language. She is the 
Pastor of Denver's House for All Sinners and Saints, where she 
ministers to many of those who present as outcasts to many 
traditional congregations. Her parishioners include members of the 
LGBTQ community, sex trade workers, and generally those who reject 
many of traditional Christian churches' teachings on such matters as 
pre-marital sex, abortion, creationism, the literal acceptance of 
bible verses and other antiquated dogma that are rejected by many 
because they simply don't make sense, or because they don't accord 
with contemporary notions of kindness and love for other human beings.

The author's parishioners feature at the center of many of the 
chapters in the book's 200 pages (with their names changed to protect 
the innocent.) The book's salient points are personified by the 
stories of church members who are recovering alcoholics and addicts, 
cutters, those who tried to live up to their churches' teachings on 
abstinence or heterosexuality, falsely believing that their strong 
contrary instincts were some form of an abomination in the eyes of a 
supposedly loving god. Bolz-Weber herself is revealing of her own 
story in an extremely vulnerable way, describing her personal 
experiences of a teen-age pregnancy and a child given up for 
adoption, a subsequent abortion, and her own struggle to attempt to 
reconcile old testament condemnations with the realities of the lives 
of her church members and a call to love rather than to condemn.

Google online reviews of this book and you will discover many 
conservative critics castigating Bolz-Weber as heretical for 
distorting what they say is the true word of God. Much of what is 
contained in the book will be offensive to orthodox Christians, 
including the author's defense of abortion and her support for the 
LGBTQ community. In the former case, she refers to scriptural 
passages that are authority for the proposition that life begins with 
breath and recounts the history of how this was once the generally 
adopted position of most Christian churches. She refers to the work 
of religious scholars who make the case that abortion became a part 
of the evangelical political agenda at a time when racist 
institutions such as Bob Jones University risked losing their 
tax-exempt status, using abortion as a means of holding the coalition 
together by grasping on to it as a new unifying issue. In response to 
those who cite various old testament verses in support of sexual 
chastity and against same-sex unions, the author notes how neither of 
these messages are contained in Christ's gospels, the central tenets 
of which are love for one's neighbor, the recognition that everyone 
is our neighbor, and that rash judgement of others is hypocritical 
when such judgement is passed by those who are themselves not 
"without sin."

Shameless will be an anathema to those who adhere to fundamentalist 
Christian beliefs. Conversely, for those who felt unwelcome in the 
traditional church because the church's teachings were innately at 
odds with their true moral compass, or because they felt like square 
pegs being forced into round holes, Nadia Bolz-Weber's understanding 
of God's love for such people offers a more welcoming message, a more 
sensible vision that is better reconciled with Christ's teachings of 
love for one another, and refusal to hate or condemn those who are 
different in ways that do not tangibly harm others. The author offers 
hope for those who feel hopeless, love for those who feel that they 
are unlovable, and worth for those who have been made to feel that 
they are worthless, merely for being who their Creator made them to 
be.
----------------------------
Reviewed on March 31, 2021

For over 30 years of faith-- a faith that never dealt seriously with 
my sexuality or had the courage to directly broach the topic I've 
searched for ministers and teachers in the faith to stand out in 
honesty and faith. Rev. booze we her dared to speak out candidly and 
with humility about the subject we all live with and deal on a day to 
day basis.

She curses, she is fragile, but this is her strength in speaking 
truth to power of how we are both sexual and spiritual beings in this 
life. She encompasses Scripture with fact and on the ground lives and 
living to make clear that our sexuality is not our enemy, but it is a 
part of our human make up and is not God shuns or is surprised by. In 
fact, she is one of the few voices in the faith to frankly say that 
our spirituality and sexuality can communion together honestly and 
with life while still upholding the hallmarks of the Gospel.

She is by far one of the best Christian voices I've had the pleasure 
to enjoy reading. This book should be in the hands of anyone who 
wants a realistic and candid approach to the subject of sex and the 
Christian faith.
